I always found it somewhat strange that when I put on a nice looking suit, I feel better. How is it that a simple change of clothes can inject significant levels of confidence into the psyche? Part of it stems from a sense of superior aesthetic -- I feel like I have an edge BECAUSE I'm more attractive to the opposite sex or otherwise, sure.But when I'm in a room full of other men, that confidence doesn't dim, so it must stem from somewhere else. My theory is that part of that confidence also occurs because we have stereotyped well-dressed people as successful. Granted, these stereotypes were established in the early to mid 1900's when the only successful women were so successful BECAUSE they married successful men, and the men usually had their clothes bought or tailored for them because that's what they liked. Like most stereotypes, it's outlived its usefulness, and now we are left with a rather pleasant sense of confidence when we dress nicely. We dress for want of success and power -- but not necessarily over the opposite sex.

But I think most of the things you apply to women could just as easily be applied to men. Sure, women will be attracted to the men with higher status but... aren't men also attracted to the women with higher status? We should be careful here because "status" can be interpreted in many different ways here -- is it lifestyle? Is it reputation? Is it physiology? People's lifestyles and reputations can change vastly depending on who you talk to; as a rule of thumb, people tend to be more attractive from a distance. but anyway, If "status" is a combination of all of those things, how can you determine which status reason is the reason a woman is appealing to? If it is a combination of several things, its seems narcissistic to assume the reason is always related to you. I don't see how what you said undermines that fact.
